<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-09-26T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-09-26T01:00:00-05:00" n="465" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d465">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">123 Service, Richard M./54:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Dooman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-26T15:00:00+09:00">September 26, 1939—3
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received September 27—9:04 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>493. Our 480, September 16, 5 p.m.<note n="65" xml:id="d465fn65">Not
                                    printed.</note> The Foreign Office has informed us orally that
                                the search of Vice Consul Service<note n="66" xml:id="d465fn66">At
                                    Chefoo.</note> was carried out by Chinese police who were
                                unacquainted with the order prohibiting search of Americans, that
                                suitable measures had been taken to inform all Chinese police of
                                that order to prevent any similar occurrences in the future and that
                                the incident had been settled locally.</p>
                            <p>Peiping please repeat to Chefoo, Chungking.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Dooman</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>